A one-way ANOVA test was performed to investigate whether sexual activity influences longevity. Given that we have 3 different types of sexual activity, we call the population means for each group $\mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3$. Our hypotheses are:

$H_0 : \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3$

$H_1 : \mu_i \neq \mu_j$ for some $(i,j)$

The chosen test is a one-way ANOVA (because we are looking at one factor's influence on one numerical outcome), with test statistic F, which has a f distribution (df= 2, 72) under $H_0$.

As can been seen from the computations, the number of days until death increases when the sexual activity decreases from high, to low, to isolated.

This one-way ANOVA test relies on the assumption that the residuals are normally distributed, with equal variances ($e$ ~ $N(0,\sigma)$). We check these assumptions here:

When looking at the residual, the normality of the residuals seems not to be satisfied, as the points in the QQ-plot approach a curved line, the left-skewed histogram and the low outliers in the boxplot. This is confirmed by a Shapiro-Wilk Test, $W =$ r shapiro.test(residuals(fruitfliesaov))[[1]], $p =$ r shapiro.test(residuals(fruitfliesaov))$p.value $< \alpha = .05$. Also, when plotting fitted values against residuals, homogeneous variance is mostly passed, as the variance seems to be equal (we see little pattern in the points), although residuals seem to vary slightly more at low fitted values. So it can be concluded that the assumption for normality is not satisfied, but the assumption of homogeneous variance is (mostly) satisfied.

We perform a Kruskal-Wallis test as the assumption of normality of the residuals was not met. Here we assume that we sample independently from a different population ($F_1, F_2, F_2$) for each condition of sexual activity.

Our hypotheses are:

$H_0 : F_1 = F_2 = F_3$

$H_1 : F_i \neq F_j$ for some $(i,j)$

b) To investigate whether sexual activity influences loglongevity, including thorax length, a ANCOVA test was performed. The thorax length was added as an explanatory variable in the previous ANOVA test.

$H_A : \alpha_i = 0$ for all i, where $\alpha_i$ is the main effect of sexual activity at level i

$H_B : \beta = 0$ , where $\beta$ is the main effect of thorax length

$H_{1A} : \alpha_i \neq 0$ for some i

$H_{1B} : \beta \neq 0$

The number of days until death increases when the sexual activity decreases from high, to low, to isolated. So sexual activity decrease loglongevity. This is seen by computing the mean values for longevity. The mean values can be computed as explained in a): $e^{mean_{loglongivity}}$. To compute the mean, we took the the mean thorax length $(\hat{\mu} = 0.825)$ into account for all sexual activity groups. Again the needed coefficients are obtained from the summary table. This results in the following means for high, isolated and low:

$\hat{\mu_{high}} = e^{1.219+0.825*2.979} = 39.45$

$\hat{\mu_{isolated}} = e^{1.219+0.410+0.825*2.979} = 59.45$

$\hat{\mu_{low}} = e^{1.219+0.286+0.825*2.979} = 52.50$

This ANCOVA test relies on the assumption that the residuals are normally distributed, with equal variances ($e$ ~ $N(0,\sigma)$). We check these assumptions in e) so they are excluded here. However the results of e) confirm that these assumption are passed. The ANCOVA also assumes no interaction. We address this assumption in part c) so it will not be investigated here either. However the results of c) confirm that there is no interaction.

c) How does thorax length influence longevity? Investigate graphically and by using an appropriate test whether this dependence is similar under all three conditions of sexual activity.

Again ANCOVA. This time the interaction effect between thorax length and sexual activity was added as an explanatory variable. To test the interaction we have the following (null)hypothesis:

$H_0 : \beta_i = \beta_j$ for all $(i,j)$, where $\beta_i$ is the main effect of thorax length for the group with sexual activity of level i

$H_1 : \beta_i \neq \beta_j$ for some $(i,j)$

d) To determine which of the two analysis, with or without thorax length, is preferred, the R-squared values are computed. Since more explanatory variables always explain more, $R^2$ always increases with more variables. Therefore we looked into the $R^2$ adjusted. These values can be obtained from the summary table of the corresponding model. The ANCOVA without thorax length in the model, has a $R^2$ adjusted of r summary(fruitfliesaov)$adj.r.squared. In contrast, for the model with thorax length taken into account the $R^2$ adjusted is r summary(fruitfliesaov2)$adj.r.squared. Since the $R^2$ adjusted of the model with thorax is higher than the $R^2$ adjusted of the model without thorax, the model with thorax is preferred. Moreover, in b) we saw the thorax length had a significant effect on longevity, so thorax length should be taken into account.

However, none of the analysis is wrong. Both analysis are carried out according to the AN(C)OVA design. Although, it is more useful to include the explanatory variable thorax length, if it is known beforehand that thorax length has an influence on the longevity of fruitflies. This way the effect of the thorax length among different groups into account can be taken into account.

First of all we make the observation that approximately 60% of the 1st class survived the tragedy, while only 42.5% of the 2nd class and 19.4% of the 3rd class survived. This implies that the Passenger class is important when predicting if an individual survives. Next to that, we see that approximately 2/3 of all women survived, while only 16.66 % of men survived, indicating that females are having a much higher survival rate. The odds mirror these ratios very well (females = 2, males = 0.2!!) When looking at the cross-factor ratios, we can see that 93.7% of individuals who were female and 1st class, survived (Odds=14.8), while first class males only have odds of 0.49.

When it comes to the Age, we first have to say that 42% of the data is missing the Age variable. We therefore drop rows containing no data for Age. We think that using the global mean or any other method to impute the Age is a foolish approach. We rather use little data than imaginary data.

  • $\beta < 0 \implies \exp(\beta) <1$ (Decreases Odds)
  • $\beta > 0 \implies \exp(\beta) >1$ (Increases Odds)

The gender has by far the lowest p-value, indicating a strong influence as we have already seen in the explanatory part. Being a male drastically decreases the linear predictor and the odds of surviving $\beta_{SEX} = -2.63$. Being 2nd or 3rd class ($\beta_{PC2} = -1.29$, $\beta_{PC3} = -2.52$) are also significantly decreasing the odds of surviving (i.e. multiplying the odds by $\exp(\beta)$, where $\exp(\beta) \ < 1 \ \forall \ \beta < 0$) yields lower odds. Increasing Age has a similar effect, $\exp(-0.03917681) = 0.961580677$, which looks like a small effect, but is almost deterministic for high ages, e.g. 70 yields $exp(70*-0.03917681)) \approx 0.06$, which is being multiplied to the odds (i.e increase in Age is associated with decrease in the probability of surviving)

d)

Propose a method to predict the survival status and a quality measure for your prediction and describe how you would implement that method (you do not need to implement it).

We would first use a randomly shuffled portion (e.g 80%) of the data to fit the model and use the model to predict the outcome of the other 20% of the data (the test set). To compare the predicted probability of survival with the actual outcome of the test set, we implement a threshold for our predictions, for example "1 if predicted >= 0.5". Then, we can obtain the accuary of that model by looking at the percent of correctly classified obervations.

f)

Is the second approach in e) wrong? Name both an advantage and a disadvantage of the two approaches, relative to each other.

Using contingency table is generally not entirely incorrect as it its straight forward in what it can measure/answer (i.e homogenity/independence). The logistic regression model has the huge advantage that it can take any set of covariates (numerical or/and factorial) and map their linear combination onto a probability space, which is not only handy for interpretation, but also very useful when it is desired to deploy the model for the usage of out of sample predictions.

  • exp($\alpha$) = exp(-0.233427404) = 0.79 is the effect on the mean of miltcoup ($\mu$), when all X = 0 and pollib_level=0
  • exp($\beta_i$) = with every unit increase in $X_i$, the predictor has a multiplicative effect of exp($\beta_i$) on the mean of miltcoup ($\mu$).
  • If $\beta_i$ = 0, then exp($\beta_i$) = 1, and the expected count is exp($\alpha$), i.e miltcoup and the predictor are not related.
  • If $\beta_i$ > 0, then exp($\beta_i$) > 1, and the expected count is exp($\beta_i$) times larger than when $X_i$ = 0
  • If $\beta_i$ < 0, then exp($\beta_i$) < 1, and the expected count is exp($\beta_i$) times smaller than when $X_i$ = 0

We see that only parties, pollib_2 and oligarchy have significant, i.e significant non-zero coefficients according to the poission model.

  • For pollib_level = 0 and X = 0 for all other variables, expected count is exp($\alpha$) = exp(-0.233427404) = 0.79
  • pollib_level = 2 decreases the expected count (multiplicative) by exp(-1.690305731)=0.184.
  • parties increases the expected count (multiplicative) by exp(0.031221156) = 1.031
  • oligarchy increases the expected count (multiplicative) by exp(0.072565776) = 1.075

Conclusion : The political liberalization level has the biggest and most dramatic impact on the occurence of military coups.

  • exp($\alpha$) = exp(0.207981) = 1.23 is the effect on the mean of Y $\mu$, when X = 0 and pollib_level = 0

  • parties increases the expected count (multiplicative) by 1.022
  • oligarchy increases the expected count (multiplicative) by 1.095
